Security Group:
---------------
A security group is a instance level firewall, can attached directly to servers ( EC2, RDS, etc.). and other resources.
> It controlls what traffic is allowed in and out.
> Stateful: If you allow inbound traffic, the return outbound traffic is automatically allowed (and vice versa).
> Only allow rules (no deny)
> By default outbound is allowed for all traffic for SG.

Default behavior:
  Inbound: Deny all by default.
  Outbound: Allow all by default.

Example:
A web server in a public subnet:
Inbound rule → allow TCP port 80 (HTTP) and 443 (HTTPS).
Outbound rule → allow all (default).

A database in a private subnet:
Inbound rule → allow TCP port 3306 (MySQL) only from the application server’s Security Group.
Outbound rule → allow all (default).

Network ACLs (NACLs):
---------------------
A NACL is subnet level firewall, attach to subnet. the rules are apply to all resources inside the subnet.
> It controls traffic entering and leaving an entire subnet.
> Stateless: You must explicitly allow both inbound and outbound traffic. Return traffic is not automatically allowed.
> Can have both allow and deny rules.
> NACLs evaluate rules in order (lowest number first) until a match is found.

Default behavior:
  Inbound: Deny all by default.
  Outbound: Deny all by default.

Example
Suppose you want to allow HTTP traffic into a subnet:
Inbound rule → allow TCP port 80 from 0.0.0.0/0.
Outbound rule → allow TCP port 1024–65535 (ephemeral ports) so responses can go back out.
If you want to block a specific IP range, you can add a deny rule for that CIDR block.








